1. 10. Seianus, here first mentioned. His early history is given in 4. 1 ; his father was mentioned in c. 7, 3.

l. 11. ceteris periculorum praemiorumque ostentator, ‘ to hold before the rest their perils and rewards.’ The context seems to show that ‘ ceteri’ are not the legions, but the troops sent from Rome, whom he was to warn how much they had to gain or lose by their behaviour.
